      "bug_description": "The algorithm has O(q²) worst‑case time complexity. For each inserted element it walks the entire chain of replacement operations that occurred after its insertion. In a test where many replacements form a long chain and many elements are inserted before the chain, the total work becomes quadratic and the program will time‑out.",
      "verdict": "CONFIRMED",
      "reasoning": "The implementation stores all replacement operations per value and, for each element, repeatedly performs a binary‑search for the next replacement after the current time, then follows that replacement and repeats. If there are R replacement queries forming a long chain (e.g., 1→2, 2→3, 3→4, …) and E elements inserted before the chain, each element will traverse the entire chain of length R, leading to O(E·R) work. In the worst case both E and R can be Θ(q) (up to 5·10⁵), giving Θ(q²) operations, which far exceeds the time limit. The described triggering input (many insertions followed by a long chain of replacements) will cause the program to run for an extremely long time, confirming the bug."
    }
  ]
}

